   font-size: 16pc; /* I meant pixels! */
 }



 Another CSS mistake I catch every so often is one I know many other folks make because I spot it too often in blog posts with code snippets:



 // This is not a CSS comment.
 .element {
   /* This is a CSS comment. */
 }



 Have you ever forgotten to use var() around a CSS variable? I sure have.



 .element {
   color: --primary-color;
 }



 Speaking of CSS variables, naming them is hard (like everything else) and I often use some incorrect version of a variable that I named!



 :root {
   --color-primary: #FF5722;
   --color-secondary: #3E2723;
 }

 /* Much later on... */

 .element {
   color: var(--primary-color); /* üôÉ */
 }



 Yes, I have indeed copied a snippet of CSS before only to have fancy quotes get in the way of making it work:



 .element::before {
   content: ‚Äú‚Äù; /* Should be "" */
 }



 And, yes, I have spent way too long figuring out those quotes were the culprit.



 Looking at that last one reminds me that I sometimes forget to set the content property when I‚Äôm working with ::before or ::after. Which reminds me of how I‚Äôve forgotten to set an element‚Äôs position before trying to offset it or change its z-index. Seriously, these things happen!


 It‚Äôs hard talking about mistakes


 Have you ever finished reading some blog post sharing some amazing trick and felt some sort of Imposter Syndrome? I think that‚Äôs largely because blog posts often mask the real work ‚Äî and failures ‚Äî that go into amazing tricks. As someone who reads posts like that for a living, I can tell you that many, if not the vast majority, go through many rounds of editing where potentially embarrassing mistakes are weeded out and smoothed over.



 Even those ridiculously awesome articles have to fail before they get all those ooooos and ahhhhhs.



 The same is true of any app, website, demo, or whatever you happen to come across. The chances any of them came out perfect the first time is next to nothin‚Äô.



 But if I‚Äôm being totally honest with you, I‚Äôm often more amazed (and interested) in the journey it takes to accomplish something, warts and all. The journey is a glimpse into what it‚Äôs like to think like a front-end developer. That‚Äôs where real (and most valuable) learning happens.



